2–93, the terrifying memories came flooding back. Cole asks, How do once-colonized peoples remember the colonial period? Drawing on a fine-grained ethnography of the social practices of remembering and forgetting in one community, she develops a practice-based approach to social memory.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBetsimisaraka (Malagasy people)xAttitudes. 0aBetsimisaraka (Malagasy people)xHistory. 0aBetsimisaraka (Malagasy people)xPsychology. 0aMemoryxSocial aspectsxMadagascarxAmbodiharina. 0aMemoryxSocial aspectszMadagascarzAmbodiharina. 0aViolencexHistoryxMadagascarxAmbodiharina. 0aViolencezMadagascarzAmbodiharinaxHistory. 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAmin, Shahid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKierkegaard, Soren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKundera, Milan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaruth, Lathy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNietzsche, Friedrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoth, Michael S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoy, Arundbati, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022846740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092682040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520926820423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.co